<section class="section section--invert manifesto" id="manifesto">
  <span class="eyebrow">§ I · Who</span>
  <div class="bias-grid manifesto__grid">
    <figure class="manifesto__figure">
      <img
        src="/images/portrait-romulus-carre.jpg"
        alt="Jack von Wiese und Kaiserswaldau"
        width="1200"
        height="1200"
        loading="lazy"
      />
      <figcaption class="mono">Portrait, 2024 · ROMULUS</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <div class="manifesto__text">
      <h2 class="manifesto__lede">
        A <span class="accent">fabulator qui coniungit</span>: a storyteller who joins things together. Founder, knight, pirate, dandy, worldbuilder.
      </h2>

      <p>
        I was born in Iowa to a family that has been getting it out of the dirt for 200 years - farmers,
        engineers, builders. I left at eighteen for the East Coast for college and then headed west to San Francisco
        - the long-walked path from a small town to a big stage. Childhood was building: LEGO, stop-motion,
        history books, costumes stitched at the kitchen table, an early conviction that the world could be re-made.
      </p>

      <p>
        At fourteen I started <strong>Back by Popular Demand</strong>, a vintage label run from a bedroom; by
        twenty-two it had moved 10,000+ pieces and paid for college zero loans. At twenty I founded
        <strong>HRMTG</strong> - Historical Reinterpretations Made Through Garments - and shipped to twelve countries
        before stepping away to build something larger.
      </p>

      <p>
        That something larger is <strong>OnTheBias</strong>: the AI layer between <em>"I have a design"</em>
        and <em>"a factory can make this."</em> 8.2 billion people get dressed every morning; somewhere
        between the sketch and the seam, the fashion industry runs on duct tape, fax sheets, and faith. I
        intend to replace that with infrastructure.
      </p>

      <p>
        I read Don Quixote in French, Italian, and Spanish - one for the heart, one for the cadence, one for
        the windmills. I speak five languages and am learning Greek as the sixth. I sculpt, I run, I dance,
        I travel. I keep a copy of Marcus Aurelius next to a copy of <em>The Tale of the Bamboo Cutter</em>.
        Everything I make is in service of a single thesis: <strong>that the next century belongs to those who
        can stitch culture, capital, and craft into one cloth - on the bias.</strong>
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<style>
  .manifesto {
    background: var(--otb-white);
    color: var(--otb-black);
  }
  .manifesto__grid {
    align-items: start;
    gap: clamp(2rem, 5vw, 5rem);
  }
  .manifesto__figure {
    margin: 0;
    position: relative;
  }
  .manifesto__figure img {
    width: 100%;
    aspect-ratio: 1 / 1;
    object-fit: cover;
    filter: contrast(1.05) saturate(0.92);
  }
  .manifesto__figure figcaption {
    margin-top: 0.65rem;
    color: var(--otb-mid-gray);
  }
  .manifesto__text {
    padding-top: 0.25rem;
  }
  .manifesto__lede {
    font-size: clamp(1.5rem, 3.2vw, 2.75rem);
    line-height: 1.12;
    letter-spacing: var(--track-tight);
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
    max-width: 22ch;
  }
  .manifesto__text p {
    font-size: var(--scale-lede);
    line-height: 1.5;
    max-width: 56ch;
  }
  .manifesto__text strong {
    font-weight: 500;
  }
</style>
